Based on the clinical presentation and the pathognomonic computed tomography finding of a dilated cecum displaced into the left upper quadrant, the diagnosis is **cecal volvulus**.

This condition occurs when the cecum, which is normally located in the right lower quadrant, twists on its mesentery. This twisting action causes a closed-loop obstruction, leading to the symptoms of acute abdominal pain, nausea, and distension. The lack of prior abdominal surgery suggests a congenital predisposition, such as an incompletely fixed cecum, which allows for this abnormal mobility and torsion.

\boxed{Cecal volvulus}
